=09
	<div class=3D"inputbar">
		<div class=3D"description0">
			<div style=3D"float:right;">
				<button class=3D"calcbutton">Show All Descriptions</button>
				<button class=3D"calcbutton">Hide All Descriptions</button>
				<br>
				<div class=3D"readallnote">
					Want to read about all of these units? Click the <span style=3D"font-w=
eight:bold;">Show All Descriptions</span> button above!
				</div>
			</div>
		=09
			<p>Magnetic units can be a confusing topic. When converting from one uni=
t to another, we often ask ourselves: "What does this unit mean?" </p>
		=09
		=09
		=09
			<p>Below are a series of magnetic unit conversion calculators with some =
explanation for each. It starts with the simplest units and builds up from =
there.<!-- If you already know what these things mean, leave the descriptio=
ns hidden.--></p>
		=09
		=09
		=09
			<br style=3D"clear:both;"><!-- CSS trick to control the height of the co=
ntainer -->
			<!--<hr>-->

		</div>
	</div>
=09
=09
	<div class=3D"inputbar">
=09
	=09
		<h2>Magnetic Flux
	=09
		<div style=3D"float:right;">
		=09
			<button class=3D"calcbutton2">Show Description</button>
			<button class=3D"calcbutton2">Hide Description</button>
		=09
		</div>
	=09
		</h2>
	=09
	=09
	=09
		<div class=3D"description description1">
			<div class=3D"KJpicc KJbigimg">
				<div class=3D"KJpic">
					<img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Measuring voltage in loop" class=3D"KJbig=
img" src=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/images/static-pages/calculator/unit=
converter.wireloop.png" width=3D"150px"></div>
			=09
			</div>
			<p>The SI (metric) unit for magnetic flux is the weber (Wb).  Where does=
 this come from?  What kind of magnetic strength does 1 weber represent?</p=
>

			<p>Imagine encircling an area with a circle of wire.  If the magnetic fl=
ux in there changes by 1 weber in a second, you'll be able to measure 1 vol=
t induced across the wire.  So: 1 weber per second equals 1 volt in the cir=
cle of wire.  Or: 1 Wb =3D 1 V s.</p>
		=09
			<p>Note that nothing is mentioned about the size of the loop of wire. It=
 doesn't matter if the loop of wire is one inch or one meter across. If you=
're measuring 1 volt across the wire, the magnetic flux is changing by 1 we=
ber per second in there.</p>
=20
		</div>
	=09
		<div class=3D"inputitem">
			<label for=3D"flux_in" class=3D"visually-hidden">Flux:</label>
			<input name=3D"flux_in" id=3D"flux_in" value=3D"1" size=3D"8" maxlength=
=3D"20" type=3D"number" step=3D"any" style=3D"width:80px;margin-bottom:.25r=
em">
			<label for=3D"units_flux_in" class=3D"visually-hidden">Flux input units:=
</label>
			<select id=3D"units_flux_in" name=3D"units_flux_in">
			=09
				<option value=3D"Wb" selected=3D"selected">weber (Wb)</option>
				<option value=3D"mWb">milliweber (mWb)</option>
				<option value=3D"microW">microweber (=C2=B5Wb)</option>
				<option value=3D"Vs">volt second (V s)</option>
				<option value=3D"line">line</option>
				<option value=3D"Mx">maxwell (Mx)</option>
				<option value=3D"Tm2">tesla m=C2=B2 (T m=C2=B2)</option>
			=09
			</select>

		</div>
	=09
		<div class=3D"equals">
			=3D
		</div>
	=09
		<div class=3D"inputitem">
			<div class=3D"output" name=3D"flux_out" id=3D"flux_out" style=3D"float:l=
eft;margin-right:4px;">1</div>
			<div style=3D"float:left;">
				<label for=3D"units_flux_out" class=3D"visually-hidden">Flux output uni=
ts:</label>
				<select id=3D"units_flux_out" name=3D"units_flux_out">
					<option value=3D"Wb">weber (Wb)</option>
					<option value=3D"mWb">milliweber (mWb)</option>
					<option value=3D"microW">microweber (=C2=B5Wb)</option>
					<option value=3D"Vs" selected=3D"selected">volt second (V s)</option>
					<option value=3D"line">line</option>
					<option value=3D"Mx">maxwell (Mx)</option>
					<option value=3D"Tm2">tesla m=C2=B2 (T m=C2=B2)</option>
				</select>
