=09

=09
	<div class=3D"inputbar">
		<h2>Magnetic Flux Density
	=09
		<div style=3D"float:right;">
		=09
			<button class=3D"calcbutton2">Show Description</button>
			<button class=3D"calcbutton2">Hide Description</button>
		=09
		</div>
	=09
		</h2>
	=09
	=09
	=09
		<div class=3D"description description2">
			<div class=3D"KJpicc KJbigimg">
				<div class=3D"KJpic">
					<img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Magnetic field of magnet in free space" c=
lass=3D"KJbigimg" src=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/images/static-pages/ca=
lculator/block1.000000-150x150.png"></div>
				<!--<div class=3D"KJcaption" style=3D"max-width:150px;">
					The strength of the magnetic flux density is indicated by the color in=
 this depiction.</div>-->
			</div>
			<p>The SI unit for flux density, or induction, is the tesla (T). This pr=
operty is also referred to as the B field.  In the equations from our <a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/blog/surface-fields-101">Surface Fields</=
a> article, we use a "B" to denote this term.</p>

			<p>Unlike Magnetic Flux above, the Flux Density defines some size for th=
e loop of wire in that example.  Flux Density is a measure how many webers =
are squeezed into some area.  In fact, webers per square meter is the unit =
for flux density. By definition, 1 weber per square meter (Wb/m<sup>2</sup>=
) =3D 1 tesla (T).</p>
           =20
            <p>The conversion between gauss and tesla is an easy one: 1 tes=
la =3D 10,000 gauss.</p>

			<p>Here's a confusing part: Many people call this, "field strength." We =
often refer to field strength in gauss. Technically, we should probably use=
 the term, "magnetic flux density," though it's much more commonly called, =
"field strength."</p>
		=09
			<ul style=3D"padding-left:20px;">
				<li>We use flux density to express <a href=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.c=
om/glossary.asp#Surface">Surface Field</a>.</li>
				<li>We use flux density to describe the "field strength" at some distan=
ce from a magnet, used in our <a href=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/magnet=
ic-unit-converter.asp?srsltid=3DAfmBOorwrNifr5oE1Z6-_bnyTgiHKbcJZD-MZ6xV323=
6egNKF61Micmq">Pull Force Calculator</a> and in the formulas given in our <=
a href=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/magnetic-unit-converter.asp?srsltid=
=3DAfmBOorwrNifr5oE1Z6-_bnyTgiHKbcJZD-MZ6xV3236egNKF61Micmq">Surface Fields=
</a> article.</li>
				<li>We measure field strength with a magnetometer, expressed in gauss.<=
/li>
				<li>The average flux density here on the surface of the <a href=3D"http=
s://www.kjmagnetics.com/blog/the-earth-is-a-magnet">earth</a> is about 0.5 =
gauss, though it varies from 0.22 to 0.6 gauss.</li>
				<li>Our magnetic field diagrams use color to indicate the strength of t=
he flux density.</li>
			</ul>

		</div>
	=09
		<div class=3D"inputitem">
			<div class=3D"inputitemlabel" title=3D"input" style=3D"display:none;">
				Input:
			</div>
			<label for=3D"mfd_in" class=3D"visually-hidden">Magnetic flux density:</=
label>
			<input name=3D"mfd_in" id=3D"mfd_in" value=3D"1" size=3D"8" maxlength=3D=
"20" type=3D"number" step=3D"any" style=3D"width:80px;margin-bottom:.25rem"=
>
			<label for=3D"units_mfd_in" class=3D"visually-hidden">Magnetic flux dens=
ity input units:</label>
			<select id=3D"units_mfd_in" name=3D"units_mfd_in">
			=09
				<option value=3D"G">gauss (G)</option>
				<option value=3D"mG">milligauss (mG)</option>
				<option value=3D"T" selected=3D"selected">tesla (T)</option>
				<option value=3D"mT">millitesla (mT)</option>
				<option value=3D"microT">microtesla (=C2=B5T)</option>
				<option value=3D"nT">nanotesla (nT)</option>
				<option value=3D"Mx/cm2">maxwell/cm=C2=B2 (Mx/cm=C2=B2)</option>
				<option value=3D"Wb/m2">weber/m=C2=B2 (Wb/m=C2=B2&gt;)</option>
			=09
			</select>

		</div>
	=09
		<div class=3D"equals">
			=3D
		</div>
	=09
		<div class=3D"inputitem">
			<div class=3D"inputitemlabel" title=3D"output" style=3D"display:none;">
				Output:
			</div>
			<div class=3D"output" name=3D"mfd_out" id=3D"mfd_out" style=3D"float:lef=
t;margin-right:4px;">10,000</div>
			<div style=3D"float:left;">
				<label for=3D"units_mfd_out" class=3D"visually-hidden">Magnetic flux de=
nsity output units:</label>
				<select id=3D"units_mfd_out" name=3D"units_mfd_out">
					<option value=3D"G" selected=3D"selected">gauss (G)</option>
					<option value=3D"mG">milligauss (mG)</option>
					<option value=3D"T">tesla (T)</option>
					<option value=3D"mT">millitesla (mT)</option>
					<option value=3D"microT">microtesla (=C2=B5T)</option>
					<option value=3D"nT">nanotesla (nT)</option>
					<option value=3D"Mx/cm2">maxwell/cm=C2=B2 (Mx/cm=C2=B2)</option>
					<option value=3D"Wb/m2">weber/m=C2=B2 (Wb/m=C2=B2)</option>
				</select>
			</div>

		</div>
	=09
		<!-- was used for debugging
		<div id=3D"fluxdens"></div>
		<div id=3D"multiplier"></div>
		-->
	=09
