	<div class=3D"inputbar">
		<h2>Magnetic Dipole Moment (m)
	=09
		<div style=3D"float:right;">
		=09
			<button class=3D"calcbutton2">Show Description</button>
			<button class=3D"calcbutton2">Hide Description</button>
		=09
		</div>
	=09
		</h2>
	=09
	=09
	=09
		<div class=3D"description description5">
			<p>We're often asked what the <a href=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/glo=
ssary.asp#DipoleMoment">dipole moment</a> of a given magnet is?  What does =
this mean?  What is the <a href=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/glossary.asp=
#DipoleMoment">dipole moment</a>?</p>

			<p>Moment is an engineering term used to describe a torque value. For ex=
ample, if you turn a bolt with 2 ft long wrench, applying 10 lb of force on=
 the end of the wrench, you would be turning the bolt with 10 x 2 =3D 20 ft=
 lb of torque<span class=3D"ref"><span class=3D"refnum">[1]</span><span cla=
ss=3D"refbody" style=3D"display: none;">If you're metrically inclined, you =
might describe a 44.5 Newton force on a 0.61 meter wrench, yielding a 27.1 =
N m torque.</span></span>.</p>

			<p>By definition, the <a href=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/glossary.as=
p#DipoleMoment">magnetic dipole moment</a> is the turning moment (the torqu=
e that's trying to rotate the magnet) that a magnet "feels" in a given magn=
etic field. Imagine placing a magnet inside a space that has a strong magne=
tic field, like the inside of an MRI machine.  The magnetic dipole moment i=
s how much torque will try rotating the magnet to align with the MRI's fiel=
d.</p>

			<p>What's a more practical, real world example? Consider a compass needl=
e. The needle itself is a magnet. If it's not pointing north (aligning itse=
lf with the earth's magnetic field), the needle will feel a torque trying t=
o rotate it towards north. It's a fairly weak torque, because the earth's m=
agnetic field is so weak (about 0.5 gauss).</p>

			<p>Units for dipole moment make sense with this mechanical description: =
newton meters per Tesla (N m / T).  That's newton meters (the torque, force=
 times distance) per Tesla (the field). If you're not used to metric units,=
 you might say the same thing as pound-feet of torque per gauss (lb ft / G)=
. Though technically correct, we've never seen anyone use this unit.</p>

			<p>Much more commonly, this unit is expressed in Ampere square meters, A=
 m<sup>2</sup>. Electrical engineers and physicists find this useful. It's =
an easy conversion: 1 A m<sup>2</sup> =3D 1 N m / T. You can calculate the =
dipole moments value yourself using this formula <a href=3D"https://www.kjm=
agnetics.com/glossary.asp#DipoleMoment">dipole moment formula</a>. Or use o=
ur online <a href=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/magnet-strength-calculator=
.asp">Pull Force Calculator</a>, which calculates the dipole moment.</p>

			<!--<p>Note: Don't confuse this with the Magnetization (often expressed =
with a capital M) of a magnet.  Magnetization (M) is a material property of=
 a magnet material which is independent of the magnet's size. M =3D magneti=
zation =3D m/V =3D dipole moment / Volume =3D Br/=EF=BF=BD<sub>0</sub>.</p>=
-->

		</div>
	=09
