				<img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Portrait of joule" class=3D"KJbigimg" src=
=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/images/static-pages/calculator/joule.jpg" h=
eight=3D"125px" width=3D"125px">
			</div>
		</div>
		The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joule">joule</a> is a unit o=
f energy named after the English physicist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/James_Prescott_Joule">James Prescott Joule</a> (1818-1889). Joule =
studied the nature of heat, and discovered its relationship to mechanical w=
ork and energy. This led to the law of conservation of energy and the first=
 law of thermodynamics.
	</div>
=09
	<div class=3D"inputitem gray">
		<div class=3D"KJpicc KJbigimg">
			<div class=3D"KJpic">
				<img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Portrait of maxwell" class=3D"KJbigimg" sr=
c=3D"https://www.kjmagnetics.com/images/static-pages/calculator/maxwell.png=
" height=3D"125px" width=3D"125px">
			</div>
		</div>
		The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell_%28unit%29">maxwell<=
/a> is named after the Scottish scientist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/James_Clerk_Maxwell">James Clerk Maxwell</a> (1831-1879). His most =
notable achievement was to formulate the classical theory of electromagneti=
c radiation, bringing together electricity, magnetism, and light as manifes=
tations of the same phenomenon. Maxwell's equations for electromagnetism ha=
ve been called the "second great unification in physics."
	</div>
=09
	<div class=3D"inputitem gray">
